column1: Who will win the election for Texas' 24th Congressional District in 2020?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
Van Duyne declared victory, but not entirely sure it's warranted, so making this 85% Republican for now.
"Votes counted: 338,960. We estimate this is 102.7% of the total vote." https://www.270towin.com/2020-election-results-live/state/texas
A sqeaker delus - 5,000 margin still counting.
Historically Republican, third parties will detract from Democratic candidate.

This will likely go to the party that wins the presidency, which is also a toss-up this year. Neither is an incumbent and neither has much polling in their favor so I'll defer to historical trends and give the Rep the advantage here.

[Post-mortem edit: Got this wrong because I did not foresee the massive hispanic swing in TX to Republicans. The idea that a permanent Democratic majority is coming due to demographics is no longer supported by the data.]
Trump is losing ground in Texas and this seat may be one that he costs them.

Massive turnout in DFW area: https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/politics/decision-2020/whats-behind-large-early-voting-turnout/2461282/ This is bad news for the Texas GOP. Voter suppression works until it doesn't. Putting my chips on the Dem here
https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-10-02/trump-says-he-and-first-lady-tested-positive-for-coronavirus

Changed my mind. I am going counter the crowd on this one. One reason is the make-up of the suburban area this district. Another reason is that covid is spiking upward again. https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2020/09/20/with-covid-19-pandemic-still-a-problem-texas-candidates-weigh-return-to-in-person-campaigning/
Outside chance the Dems capture this seat but unlikely.

This is a 50/50 one in which the crowd is overestimating GOP chances. Democrat has higher odds than the crowd says because: 1) Congressional races are tough to poll, but still, Valenzuela did well in last month's polls: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/house/texas/ 2) Trump is only up by 1.0 in Texas's polling average: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/president-general/texas/ 3) Suburban districts like this one have been trending blue since 2016. Republican barely won in 2018, despite being a long-time incumbent. 4) Demographic changes. For decades the Hispanic population has been increasing in Texas, and now it is finally starting to vote in large numbers: https://www.texastribune.org/2020/06/25/texas-hispanic-population-grows-2-million/ https://www.houstonchronicle.com/politics/texas/article/Latino-voters-in-Texas-much-more-motivated-15458880.php
Closer than one might think.
Not confident... but curious as to how this will shake out.
Chances are good this seat stays with Republican hands but the fact the Democratic candidate is Hispanic along with Biden's VP choice energizing black voters, the seat could flip.

This marks one of the few toss-ups where the incumbent is not running for re-election, so the advantage is almost entirely historical. It is seen as most pundits as either a toss-up or a leaning red district, which I think is a reasonable projection. Its retiring representative is a Republican who has served in the House since 2004, and while he only won by 3 points in the 2018 election, a 16 year tenure should not be taken for granted. Furthermore, Trump is up by around 6 points in the district, suggesting that a Dem swing due to inadequate voter turnout or Republican disenfranchisement is unlikely. The race will likely be close, but given that there are few demonstrable advantages for the Democrats, I'd say its the Republicans to lose.
Poll-based forecast. A lot of variance right now!
Polls in Aug 5th and July 14th indicate a modest lead of Dem. Valenzuela against the Republican Van Duyne. https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/house/texas/
https://www.businessinsider.com/candace-valenzuela-texas-congress-black-latina-2020-8

I am originally from Texas - Dallas metro. Valenzuela can definitely win this open seat in a district that Trump only won 51/46 in 2016 and that Marchant barely held in 2018 (Beto won this district) - the major cities in Texas, and many of their suburbs, are turning more D. Marchant announced his retirement for a reason. That said, Van Duyne is well-known in the area as the former mayor of Irving and Valenzuela is an outsider with a limited resume. I think if Biden/Harris win, then this district will flip too.

This is not hospitable country for Ds--especially, not to put too fine a point on it, if they are called Valenzuela and are running against a blonde person. This is a district that, unless carefully gerrymandered, will go D sooner or later, but not this time.
